rewar origins of the consumer engine that was to take off under the American Occupation, Partner quickly turns his sights on the business leaders, inventors, laborers, and ordinary citizens who participated in the broadly successful effort to create new markets for expensive, unfamiliar new products.Throughout, the author relates these pressure-cooker years in Japan to the key themes of twentieth-century experience worldwide: the role of technology in promoting social change, the rise of mass consumer societies, and the construction of gender in advanced industrial economies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConsumerszJapan. 0aElectronic industrieszJapan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  a20th century japanese culture.  a20th century japanese history.  aamerican occupation.  aasian economics.  aasian history.  abusiness leadership.  aconsumer culture.  aconsumerism.  acultural studies.  aelectrical goods.  aexport government policy.  aindustrial economics.  ajapan.  ajapanese consumer.  ajapanese electronics industry.  amass consumer society.  amatsushita.  aministry of international trade and industry.  asocial change.  asony.  astudy of the east asian institute columbia university series.  atoshiba.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021939740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520923171?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520923171423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520923171/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY